      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: Subscribers to Capitol Connection, a microwave television broadcast service provided by George Mason University, were surprised yesterday morning to turn on their sets expecting to receive the joint Congressional hearings into the Iran-contra affair and instead see a business meeting of the Federal Communications</p>
        <p>Subscribers to Capitol Connection, a microwave television broadcast service provided by George Mason University, were surprised yesterday morning to turn on their sets expecting to receive the joint Congressional hearings into the Iran-contra affair and instead see a business meeting of the Federal Communications Commission.</p>
        <p>''It really hit the fan; we were bombarded by phone calls,'' said Michael R. Kelley, who is director of telecommunications for the university. He added that the station immediately switched back to televising the Congressional hearings.</p>
        <p>It seems that the service normally broadcasts F.C.C. hearings a couple of times a month. Mr. Kelley said he ''fell asleep'' watching the previous day's testimony by Robert C. McFarlane, President Reagan's former national security adviser, and assumed that other viewers were equally bored. So he decided to televise the F.C.C. for the first hour or so of the morning.</p>
        <p>''Boy, did we get shot down fast,'' Mr. Kelley said. ''We definitely made the wrong decision.''  WASHINGTON TALK: BRIEFING</p>
      </block>
